                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">A lot of the choices on AAs here are based on your personal playstyle, so rather than reccomending an exact path, i've broken it into teirs.  Before you move to the next teir, i would very strongly reccommend finishing the one you're on tho.  
<br />
Teir 1:
<br />
SCM3:This is basically a must get AA.  The mana saved by this AA is pretty rediculously high, and can help a ton when you get the unlucky 2-3 breaks in a row.  Add'ly, saving mana means you have to regen less to cast a spell, so it allows you to do significantly more.
<br />

<br />
Mez mastery:While you're not gonna be using this on pookas, its a godsend vs everything else, especially in LDoNs.  Not only does it have a huge impact on charming, it's very useful in many other situations.(yea, i kno, saving 20 AA's at once sucks, but it is -completely- worth it even within the 1st 100 AAs)
<br />

<br />
TD3:  While i'm sure plenty of people here will disagree with me, i noticed more of a difference between as i went from TD 2 to 3 than 1 to 2.  Timeing charm to max duration helps a ton once you have TD3, if you plan on charming much, timing it's something i'd try to get used to.  Charm breaks you can see coming are cake, debuffers are on the ready, you can get some distance between you and the pet, and you can tell the puller to hold for a moment so u wont have other mobs to worry about.  This strategy's a lot more effective with TD3, but can obviously be used without it with some success.
<br />

<br />
Teir 2:
<br />
CA/LR5:widely recognised as a solid defensive AA for chanters
<br />
Planar power(assuming you have the cha to get to 305):While its not universal, i've heard quite a number of poeple say 305 cha has a quite noticable impact on your avg charm duration.(vs the 280 u should either already have, or be working toward, as it does affect your charm durations, and everyhing else you can do to affect them should already be maxed)
<br />

<br />
Channeling focus 3:While i'm not as sure on this as the other teir 2 AA's for charming, it will prolly be more valuable than any of the teir 3 AA's in regards to charming outside of vxed or above GoD.  If you're only looking at vxed+, I might put this in teir 3 as youre generally gonna be keeping quite some distance between u and ur pet as 1 stun vs a hasted dual weilding pooka can earn you a free trip to your bind point in very short order.
<br />

<br />
Teir 3:
<br />
ND3:HP are HP, and this nets ya a decent # of 'em
<br />
QB3:as it relates to charming this isnt great, but it's a solid AA and does have some limited use related to charming.  Overall i'd move it up to tier 2, but as it relates to charming I just dont feel it's justified there
<br />

<br />
SCS3:I'd prolly rate this teir 2 overall, teir 3 in regards to charming.  This goes up to teir 2 if You use the following strategy, and it doesnt work with only scs2.  On pet break, with scs3, if you tash your pet, and someone ensares it, if the snarer sits, they gain agro, if they stand, they give you agro.  (note, have been having trouble with this in GoD recently, and snarers have had to snare 2x times to get the agro to pingpong)  Of course if this works with scs2, this stays tier 3, and if your ranger or dru's not on top of their game, they wont snare it in time, so once again, it stays teir 3.
<br />

<br />
CS3/ID5:See the numerous threads on this board which discuss the usefulness or lack thereof of this AA.  Prolly worth getting before 250AA or so, but i dont know how much sooner than that.
<br />

<br />
Tier 4(i.e. usless AAs):
<br />
Pesistant casting:see the threads discussing how uselessly rare this AA actually triggers.  If it worked resonably often i'd prolly move it up to teir 2 for ldon, and teir 3 for everything else.
<br />
Sta/Agi AAs
<br />
perm illusion:as it relates to charming i feel this is a pretty usless AA unless you're soloing for hours on end</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
